}}</ref> A bird-adapted strain of H5N1, called HPAI A(H5N1) for "highly [[pathogen]]ic avian influenza virus of type A of subtype H5N1", is the causative agent of [[transmission and infection of H5N1|H5N1 flu]], commonly known as "avian influenza" or "bird flu". It is [[endemic (epidemiology)|endemic]] in many bird populations, especially in Southeast Asia. One strain of HPAI A(H5N1) is [[global spread of H5N1|spreading globally]] after first appearing in Asia. It is [[epizootic]] (an epidemic in nonhumans) and panzootic (affecting animals of many species, especially over a wide area), killing tens of millions of birds and spurring the [[culling]] of hundreds of millions of others to stem its spread. Most mentions of "bird flu" and H5N1 in the media refer to this strain.<ref name=KSLi>

